Antenna Problem¶

In designing antennas that effectively transmit and receive signals at specific frequencies, understanding key performance metrics is essential. One such metric is the S11 parameter, also known as "return loss," which measures how much of a signal is reflected back rather than radiated effectively. A low S11 value at desired frequencies indicates efficient radiation, crucial for high-frequency communication systems like those used in 5G technology.

However, evaluating S11 across a wide range of frequencies requires complex electromagnetic simulations, which are computationally intensive and time-consuming. This complexity makes optimizing antenna designs through trial and error challenging, particularly when exploring numerous geometric configurations and material properties.

This assignment aims to explore the relationships between the design parameters of an antenna and its electromagnetic performance using machine learning techniques such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and regression modeling. By applying these methods, the goal is to simplify the complex relationships within the S11 dataset, identify influential design parameters, and develop predictive models that can support efficient antenna design and performance analysis.

For this problem there are two types of target variables. The real part of S11 represents how much of the signal’s power is reflected directly back without any time delay.The imaginary part represents how much of the reflected signal is shifted in phase relative to the transmitted signal. Also there are 201 frequencies, for the sack of simplicity 2 key frequencies are selected.

2. Data Preprocessing & PCA¶

To simplfy the computation 2 frequencies are selected. Then %20 of the data is divided randomly as test set. After the train and test split train data is scaled using standard scaler that scales the data according to noral distribution. Using the mean and standard deviation test data is also scaled. Then, the data is ready to apply PCA.

In [88]:
selected_freq_indices = [70,120]
real_selected = real_data.iloc[:, selected_freq_indices]
img_selected = img_data.iloc[:, selected_freq_indices]

# Split data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train_real, y_test_real = train_test_split(input_data, real_selected, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)
X_train, X_test, y_train_img, y_test_img = train_test_split(input_data, img_selected, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

In [70]:
# Scale design parameters based on training data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# 4. Dimensionality Reduction with PCA
pca = PCA()
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train_scaled)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test_scaled)

# Check explained variance ratio
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
print("Explained variance by each principal component:", explained_variance)

# Plot explained variance to determine the number of components
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(np.cumsum(explained_variance), marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.title('Explained Variance vs. Number of Components')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Explained variance by each principal component: [0.20714834 0.11121812 0.10869435 0.10224376 0.09342887 0.08728294
 0.08165724 0.07856563 0.06632053 0.05688063 0.00655959]

According to the plot above, choosing first 10 component cover more than %99 of the variance. So by applying PCA, we are reducing the number of features 1. However to simplfy the model even more, first nine of them can be also selected because they cover %93 of the variance.

In [71]:
coefficients = pd.DataFrame(
    pca.components_,
    columns=input_data.columns,  
    index=[f"PC{i+1}" for i in range(len(pca.components_))]  
)

# Identify the most important features for PC1
pc1_coeff = coefficients.loc["PC1"]
most_important_features_pc1 = pc1_coeff.abs().sort_values(ascending=False)
# Plot loadings for PC1
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(coefficients.columns, pc1_coeff)
plt.xlabel("Design Parameters")
plt.ylabel("Coefficients for PC1")
plt.title("PCA Coefficients for PC1")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid()
plt.show()

The first 2 of the components covers around %30 of the data and when we checked the pca coefficients of PC1 and PC2 width of patch and hight of the patch are the most important features for S11 value. Also for PC1 c_antipad abd c_probe are important.

# Combine input features and selected outputs
combined_data = pd.concat([input_data, real_selected, img_selected], axis=1)

# Compute the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = combined_data.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
sns.heatmap(
    correlation_matrix, 
    annot=False,  # Set to True to see correlation values
    cmap="coolwarm", 
    cbar=True
)
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Design Parameters and Outputs")
plt.show()

According to the correlation matrix most correlated features for real part are width of patch and height of substrate, they are correlated with real part positively while for imaginary part they are negatively correlated. On the other hand, these two features are highly correlated with each other. So, for the model one of them could be enough. The relation between target(real or imaginary) and geometric features are shown below. It appears that width of patch and hight of substrate has a nonlinear relation with the target. So, applying linear regression may not be the answer.

# 7. Regression Modeling for Real Part of S11
real_model = LinearRegression()
real_model.fit(X_train, y_train_real)
y_pred_real = real_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate real part model
print("Real Part - Mean Squared Error:", mean_squared_error(y_test_real, y_pred_real))
print("Real Part - R^2 Score:", r2_score(y_test_real, y_pred_real))

Real Part - Mean Squared Error: 0.09408048092385574
Real Part - R^2 Score: 0.7663526689226714

imginary Part - Mean Squared Error: 0.08220579093005698
imginary Part - R^2 Score: 0.16105609931580278

Results: According to the prediction vs actual plots, our models failed to fully capture the nonlinearity in the data which is expected. Because PCA and linear regression assume linear relationships between features and the target. However, for this example some of the features have nonlinearity. To deal with this problem nonlinear terms can be added to the model. Aldo other modelling approaches that more suitable for nonlinear problems may be helpful such as regression trees, boosting models etc.

Note: Some codes for the plots are edited using ChatGPT.
